{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2370"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2370"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.03,0.7,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52037"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"2496"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44778"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52037"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of severe shortness of breath, unable to complete full sentences. This is on the background of increasing breathlessness on exertion over the past three months. He has also noticed some muscle wasting and diminished appetite during this time. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He drinks five glasses of wine daily and has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 89% on 2 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula, and temperature 37.9\u00b0C. There is dullness to percussion at the left base of his chest with reduced breath sounds. A chest X-ray is taken (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause for the radiographic findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumonia","Congestive heart failure","Liver cirrhosis","Lung malignancy","Pancreatitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiograph demonstrates a large left sided pleural effusion. The most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s recent deterioration and radiographic findings, is a large pleural effusion secondary to \u003Cstrong\u003Elung malignancy\u003C/strong\u003E. This diagnosis is supported by several factors in the clinical presentation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Progressive dyspnoea over three months\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Constitutional symptoms (muscle wasting and anorexia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Significant smoking history (30 pack-years)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Absence of other obvious causes (e.g., heart failure, liver disease)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause an exudative pleural effusion, but the subacute onset and lack of productive cough or high fever make this less likely as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes bilateral pleural effusions and is usually associated with other signs of fluid overload (e.g., peripheral oedema, raised JVP). The patient has no known cardiac history, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to a transudative pleural effusion (hepatic hydrothorax), but there\u0027s no mention of liver disease or signs of portal hypertension. While the patient drinks alcohol regularly, cirrhosis severe enough to cause a large pleural effusion would likely have other manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can rarely cause a left-sided pleural effusion, but the absence of abdominal pain makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while the clinical picture strongly suggests malignancy, definitive diagnosis requires analysis of the pleural fluid. Light\u0027s criteria are used to differentiate between exudative and transudative effusions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Pleural fluid protein : serum protein \u0026gt; 0.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Pleural fluid LDH : serum LDH \u0026gt; 0.6\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Pleural fluid LDH \u0026gt; 2/3 upper limit for serum LDH\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn exudative effusion is likely when any of the above criteria are met; transudative when none are met. Malignant effusions are typically exudative. Further investigations, including cytology of the pleural fluid and potentially a CT scan of the chest, would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis of lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Breathlessness from a pleural effusion is a well-recognised presenting symptom of bronchogenic carcinoma.","Light\u0027s criteria are used to differentiate between exudative and transudative pleural effusions.","Smoking history and constitutional symptoms are important risk factors for lung cancer."],"references":["Porcel JM, Light RW. Diagnostic Approach to Pleural Effusion in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2006; 73(7): 1211-1220. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2006/0401/p1211.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2370"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17810"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17810"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f552b8de-7c0f-496a-8ef9-f32d705ba705.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f552b8de-7c0f-496a-8ef9-f32d705ba705.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":529,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T09:51:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:52:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2370"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52037"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat